\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 1 (15 points):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A=LU$
\end_inset

 has the LU factors 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
1\\
-2 & 1\\
0 & -2 & 1\\
-1 & -1 & -2 & 1
\end{array}\right),\;U=\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & -1 & -2 & 0\\
 & 1 & 0 & -2\\
 &  & 1 & 0\\
 &  &  & 1
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\left(\begin{array}{c}
-1\\
2\\
2\\
-4
\end{array}\right),$
\end_inset

 what is 
\begin_inset Formula $x=A^{-1}b$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Assuming you solved the previous part efficiently, roughly how much more
 arithmetic operations would be required for the same approach if the matrices
 were 
\begin_inset Formula $8\times8$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times4$
\end_inset

? It should be about 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
underline{
\backslash
hspace{3em}}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 times more.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If you form a new 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times5$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
A & b\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

 by appending the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 (from above) as an extra column after 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and perform the 
\emph on
same
\emph default
 elimination steps as were used to get the LU factors above, what upper-triangul
ar matrix would you obtain? (Hint: if you did part (a) properly, this part
 can be done with 
\emph on
no arithmetic
\emph default
.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Solution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $x=A^{-1}b$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $b=Ax=LUx$
\end_inset

.
 So, to solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 we can solve the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $b=Ly$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and then 
\begin_inset Formula $y=Ux$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, and these can be solved 
\series bold
by forward/back substitution
\series default
.
 The forward substitution procedure for solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 gives: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{1}=-1
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-2y_{1}+y_{2}=2\implies y_{2}=2+2y_{1}=2+2*(-1)=0
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0y_{1}-2y_{2}+y_{3}=2\implies y_{3}=2+2y_{2}=2+2*0=2
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-y_{1}-y_{2}-2y_{2}+y_{4}=-4\implies y_{4}=-4+y_{1}+y_{2}+2y_{3}=-4+(-1)+0+2*2=-1
\]

\end_inset

Then we can solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 using back substitution: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{4}=-1
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{3}=2
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{2}-2x_{4}=0\implies x_{2}=2x_{4}=-2
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{1}-x_{2}-2x_{3}=-1\implies x_{1}=-1+x_{2}+2x_{3}=-1+(-2)+2*2=1
\]

\end_inset

So the solution is 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{x=(1,-2,2,-1)}.$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
Note
\series default
: Contrary to popular opinion, you 
\emph on
cannot invert
\emph default
 a lower/upper-triangular matrix simply by flipping the signs below/above
 the diagonal.
 (This only works for very special triangular matrices, e.g.
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

elementary
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 matrices representing a single elimination step.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

You could also do this problem by multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $LU$
\end_inset

 to get 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and then proceed with Gaussian elimination as usual.
 But this is just going in a circle: elimination on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 will give you back 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

! Quantitatively, using this inefficient approach requires 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim m^{3}$
\end_inset

 operations rather than the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim m^{2}$
\end_inset

 for forward/back-substitution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Back or forward substitution for 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times m$
\end_inset

 systems require 
\begin_inset Formula $~m^{2}$
\end_inset

 operations.
 So, the ratio of the time required for 
\begin_inset Formula $m=8$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m=4$
\end_inset

 is about 
\begin_inset Formula $8^{2}/4^{2}=2^{2}=\boxed{4}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Recall that row operations are given by multiplication on the left by an
 invertible matrix.
 The Gaussian elimination giving 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is given by multiplication by an elimination matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $EA=U$
\end_inset

, and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $E=L^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 So, performing the same elimination steps to 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\begin{pmatrix}A & b\end{pmatrix}$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{-1}B=(L^{-1}AL^{-1}b)=(U,L^{-1}b)$
\end_inset

.
 In part (1) we solved 
\begin_inset Formula $Ly=b$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{-1}b=y=(-1,0,2,-1).$
\end_inset

 So we obtain the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{\begin{pmatrix}U & y\end{pmatrix}}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 as in the problem statement and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 as computed in the solution to part (1).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 2 (15 points):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You are given the recurrence relation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(2I+B^{T}B)x_{n+1}=(2I-B^{T}B)x_{n}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is a real 
\begin_inset Formula $5\times3$
\end_inset

 matrix.
 We start with a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 and compute 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2},\ldots$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}=A^{n}x_{0}$
\end_inset

 for some matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

).
 What is 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{T}B$
\end_inset

 , give an eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Circle all possible
\series default
 behaviors of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 for large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, given the information above: 
\series bold
decaying
\series default
 to zero, 
\series bold
oscillating
\series default
 but not growing or decaying in length, going to a 
\series bold
nonzero constant
\series default
 vector, or 
\series bold
growing
\series default
 longer and longer.
 Explain your answers by giving some property (or properties) that must
 be true of the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=0$
\end_inset

 for a nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

, give one of the singular values (
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

) of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Solution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{T}B$
\end_inset

 is symmetric positive semidefinite by construction, so all of its eigenvalues
 are real and nonnegative.
 So the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $2I+B^{T}B$
\end_inset

 are all real and at least 2, so in particular it has no eigenvalue equal
 to zero and hence is invertible.
 Therefore we can rearrange the recurrence relation to: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{n+1}=(2I+B^{T}B)^{-1}(2I-B^{T}B)x_{n}
\]

\end_inset

and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n+1}=Ax_{n}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the marix 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{A=(2I+B^{T}B)^{-1}(2I-B^{T}B)}$
\end_inset

.
 To see that this really gives the right matrix, notice that we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=Ax_{0}$
\end_inset

, but also 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}=Ax_{1}=AAx_{0}=A^{2}x_{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}=Ax_{2}=AA^{2}x_{0}=A^{3}x_{0}$
\end_inset

, etc.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

It may be tempting to write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2I+B^{T}B}{2I-B^{T}B}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, but we don't use the expression 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\frac{C}{D}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is not defined for matrices because it is ambiguous: is it 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{-1}C$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $CD^{-1}$
\end_inset

? (Although in this particular case the numerator and denominator matrices
 commute.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvector for 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{T}B$
\end_inset

 with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is also an eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $2I+B^{T}B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2I-B^{T}B$
\end_inset

, with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $2+\lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2-\lambda$
\end_inset

, respectively, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is also an eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $(2I+B^{T}B)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $1/(2+\lambda)$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is also an eigenvector for 
\begin_inset Formula $A=(2I+B^{T}B)^{-1}(2I-B^{T}B)$
\end_inset

 with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{\frac{2-\lambda}{2+\lambda}.\ensuremath{}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
As 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{T}B$
\end_inset

 is symmetric positive semidefinite all of its eigenvalues are real and
 nonnegative.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\geq0$
\end_inset

 is a nonnegative number, then 
\begin_inset Formula $-1<(2-\lambda)/(2+\lambda)\leq1$
\end_inset

 (and you can't do any better than those upper and lower bounds).
 Note, in particular, that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

 would give an eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, so this is a possibility.
 Furthermore, the argument in (2) actually implies that any basis of eigenvector
s for 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{T}B$
\end_inset

 (which is diagonalizable because it is real symmetric) is also a basis
 of eigenvectors for 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (with the eigenvalues transformed according to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\mapsto(2-\lambda)/(2+\lambda)$
\end_inset

).
 All of the eigenvalues are real numbers in the half-open interval (-1,1],
 so the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x_{n}\}_{n}$
\end_inset

 cannot grow large or oscillate.
 It can decay, if all of the eigenvectors appearing in the decomposition
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 into a linear combination of eigenvectors have eigenvalue wth magnitude
 less than 1, and it can go to a constant if there is an eigenvector with
 eigenvalue 1 appearing with nonzero constant in the decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{\text{decaying and going to a nonzero constant should be circled, and nothing else.}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=Ax_{0}$
\end_inset

 to be zero with 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 nonzero means that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in N(A)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvector for 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 with eigenvalue 0.
 This can only happen if 
\begin_inset Formula $(2-\lambda)/(2+\lambda)=0$
\end_inset

 for some eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{T}B$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{T}B$
\end_inset

 must have an eigenvalue equal to 2.
 The singular values of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are the positive square roots of the positive eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{T}B$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{\sqrt{2}}$
\end_inset

 is a singular value of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 3 (15 points):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The distance between a point 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and a plane in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 is defined as the 
\emph on
minimum
\emph default
 distance 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert b-y\Vert$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 point 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in the plane.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose the points 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in the plane are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $y=c+\alpha a_{1}+\beta a_{2}$
\end_inset

 for all real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, given vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $c,a_{1},a_{2}\in\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 that define the plane (
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}$
\end_inset

 are linearly independent).
 Under 
\series bold
what condition(s)
\series default
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $c,a_{1},a_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the plane a 
\series bold
subspace
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Write down a 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
system of equations
\series default
, in terms of the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},a_{2,}c,b$
\end_inset

 (or matrices defined from these vectors) whose solution gives the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{array}{c}
\alpha\\
\beta
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

 for the 
\emph on
closest
\emph default
 point 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in the plane to 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For this closest point 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b-y$
\end_inset

 is in 
\series bold
what subspace
\series default
 of the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left(a_{1}a_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

? What is the 
\series bold
dimension
\series default
 of this subspace?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}=\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
2\\
1
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}=\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
0\\
0
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\series bold
find a vector
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 such that the distance between any point 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and the plane is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $|d^{T}(b-c)|$
\end_inset

.
 
\series bold
What subspace
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Solution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Subspaces have to contain the zero vector, so there have to be real numbers
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{c},\beta_{c}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $c+\alpha_{c}a_{1}+\beta a_{c2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 But then 
\begin_inset Formula $c=-\alpha_{c}a_{1}-\beta_{c}a_{2}$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{c\in\text{span}(a_{1},a_{2})}.$
\end_inset

 To see that this necessary condition is also sufficient, notice that in
 this case the points on the plane are those points 
\begin_inset Formula $c+\alpha a_{1}+\beta a_{2}=(\alpha+\alpha_{c})a_{1}+(\beta+\beta_{c})a_{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta$
\end_inset

 are arbitrary real numbers, which is just the span of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}$
\end_inset

, which is indeed a subspace (although if 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}$
\end_inset

 are dependent as well, the subspace is no longer a plane).
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
Note: 
\series default
While the question intended to ask for a condition on 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, the original phrasing (which had omitted the words 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

on 
\begin_inset Formula $c,a_{1},a_{2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) was somewhat ambiguous in hindsight, so we gave full credit to solutions
 that described only the general conditions for a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 to be a subspace.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Take any point 
\begin_inset Formula $y=c+\alpha a_{1}+\beta a_{2}$
\end_inset

 on the plane.
 Then its distance to 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Vert y-b\Vert=c+\alpha a_{1}+\beta a_{2}-b\Vert=\Vert\begin{pmatrix}a_{1} & a_{2}\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}\alpha\\
\beta
\end{pmatrix}-(b-c)\Vert
\]

\end_inset

 (notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\begin{pmatrix}a_{1} & a_{2}\end{pmatrix}$
\end_inset

 is a 3 by 2 matrix with columns given by the 3 by 1 vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}$
\end_inset

).
 We want to choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta$
\end_inset

 to make this distance (or its square) as small as possible, which is the
 usual least squares problem for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert Ax-v\Vert^{2}$
\end_inset

 where in this case 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\begin{pmatrix}a_{1} & a_{2}\end{pmatrix}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\begin{pmatrix}\alpha\\
\beta
\end{pmatrix}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $v=b-c$
\end_inset

.
 A vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\begin{pmatrix}\alpha\\
\beta
\end{pmatrix}$
\end_inset

 will describe a point 
\begin_inset Formula $y=c+\alpha a_{1}+\beta a_{2}$
\end_inset

 minimizing the distance to 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 if and only if the associated normal equations for this least squares problem
 are satisfied, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A^{T}A\begin{pmatrix}\alpha\\
\beta
\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}a_{1}^{T}\\
a_{2}^{T}
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}a_{1} & a_{2}\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}\alpha\\
\beta
\end{pmatrix}=A^{T}(b-c)=\begin{pmatrix}a_{1}^{T}\\
a_{2}^{T}
\end{pmatrix}(b-c).
\]

\end_inset

 Multiplying together the first two matrices on the left and right, this
 reads: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{\begin{pmatrix}a_{1}^{T}a_{1} & a_{1}^{T}a_{2}\\
a_{2}^{T}a_{1} & a_{2}^{T}a_{2}
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}\alpha\\
\beta
\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}a_{1}^{T}(b-c)\\
a_{2}^{T}(b-c)
\end{pmatrix}}
\]

\end_inset

which is a 2 by 2 system of equations in 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta$
\end_inset

, as needed.
\end_layout

