 is real symmetric, the corresponding eigenvectors 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1},v_{2},v_{3}$
\end_inset

 must be orthogonal.
 So also 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1},v_{2},v_{3}$
\end_inset

 is an orthogonal basis (not necessarily orthonormal, although they could
 be rescaled to be orthonormal!) consisting of eigenvectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 with corresponding eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $1,1/2,1/3$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 So the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is the sum of three rank-1 matrices (orthogonal projections onto the eigenvecto
rs): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A^{-1}=\frac{v_{1}v_{1}^{T}}{v_{1}^{T}v_{1}}+\frac{1}{2}\frac{v_{2}v_{2}^{T}}{v_{2}^{T}v_{2}}+\frac{1}{3}\frac{v_{3}v_{3}^{T}}{v_{3}^{T}v_{3}}
\]

\end_inset

 so the desired expression is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{\left(\frac{v_{1}v_{1}^{T}}{v_{1}^{T}v_{1}}+\frac{1}{2}\frac{v_{2}v_{2}^{T}}{v_{2}^{T}v_{2}}+\frac{1}{3}\frac{v_{3}v_{3}^{T}}{v_{3}^{T}v_{3}}\right)b}.
