\begin_layout Enumerate
The eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{T}A$
\end_inset

 are the squares of the signular values of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and the determinant is the product of the eigenvalues, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{\det(A^{T}A)=\sigma_{1}^{2}\sigma_{2}^{2}\sigma_{3}^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 The singular value decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $A=U\Sigma V^{T}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $U,V$
\end_inset

 are orthogonal matrices and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is the diagonal matrix with diagonal entries 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{1},\sigma_{2},\sigma_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(A)=\det(U)\det(\Sigma)\det(V^{T})$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is diagonal we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(\Sigma)=\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}\sigma_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The determinant of an orthogonal matrix is 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

, so we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{|\det(A)|=\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}\sigma_{3}}.$
\end_inset

 Alternatively, 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(A^{T}A)=\det(A^{T})\det(A)=\det(A)^{2}$
\end_inset

, so we again obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $|\det(A)|=\sqrt{\det(A^{T}A)}=\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}\sigma_{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

